fields.summary: Error Message is shown when saving after removing all PU:s
fields.description:
An error message is shown when all production units are removed and I click on the Save button. See the attached image file.

*To reproduce*
1. Open the production units tab for an order with at least one production unit assigned to it (or add one or more production units to an order and click on the save button).
2. Click on the edit button.
3. Remove all the production units and click on the Save button.

*Expected Result*
All production units previously assigned to the order are the removed. (i.e. no production units are assigned to the order).

*Actual Result*
An error message is shown and it is not possible to Save the changes.

fields.description:
As a user
I only want to see shipping info if the TOD, QTY or MOT is changed
so that no duplicates are shown, only unique shipping info

Please note!
There is a need to run the database scripts for cleanup once again when this CR goes into production (SQL which we will execute for OFU-2395)

*Scenario 1: No changes in TOD, QTY or MOT*
Given that a shipping info is displayed for a planning market for an order
AND that a new shipping info is received with no changes on TOD, QTY or MOT
When the delivery history is shown for the planning market
THEN no new history item has been created for the new shipping info

*Scenario 2: Updated TOD, QTY or MOT*
Given that a shipping info is displayed for a planning market for an order
AND that a new shipping info is received with changes on either TOD, QTY or MOT
When the delivery history is shown for the planning market
THEN a new history item has been created for the new shipping info

*Scenario 3: New Shipping info*
Given that no shipping info is displayed for a planning market for an order
AND that a new shipping info is received
When the delivery history is shown for the planning market
THEN A new history item has been created for the new shipping info

items.fromString:
DB patch framework cannot handle additions in earlier branches when newer branch is already in place. If new scripts has been added in release 11, then these will be added before latest script in release 12, which makes the patcher crash in the installation situation.

solution 1:
deploy all scripts if they have not been executed already, regardless of script ordering. Scripts can be executed several times but will only be applied once (PUT-ptotocol pattern). If the script's name is in the Appliedpatches table, then it will not be executed.

solution 2:
the scripts are always written in an "IF EXISTS (...)" manner. They will always be rerun, even if already installed. Pros and cons: this way helps when developing scripts but it also involves more script programming. Autotests needed.
solution 2: 
when merged to new release 12, then also add them to a "skip" list so that they will be ignored by patcher. The script-files might be empty because they will be ignored. We also need to add the real scripts last in patch-list. This might involve modifying the scripts to work after the other rel12 scirpts, instead of before. Autotests needed!

fields.description:
*Acc criteria for SIT test*
configuration "Accept all" is enough 
--------------------------------------------------------


During the gradual roll-out Mike and Nellie imports need to ignore data that does not belong to the current release. A filter will be introduced based on which department the data relates to. Initially all data is in Mike. Gradually data will be moved to Nellie (based on which department it belongs to).

*Scenario 1: Filter out orders +not+ rolled out*
Given a department "Shirts" that has +not+ been rolled out 
And an order "12345" that is for a product belonging to the "Shirt" department
When order "12345" is imported
Then I should see the order "12345" in +Mike version+
But I should +not+ see the order "12345" in +Nellie version+

*Scenario 2: Filter out orders rolled out*
Given a department "Shirts" that has been rolled out 
And an order "12345" that is for a product belonging to the "Shirt" department
When order "12345" is imported
Then I should see the order "12345" in +Nellie version+
But I should +not+ see the order "12345" in +Mike version+

*Scenario 3: Filter out products +not+ rolled out*
Given a department "Shirts" that has +not+ been rolled out 
And a product "12345" that belongs to the "Shirt" department
When product"12345" is imported
Then I should see the product "12345" in +Mike version+
But I should +not+ see the product "12345" in +Nellie version+

*Scenario 4: Filter out products rolled out*
Given a department "Shirts" that has been rolled out 
And a product "12345" that belongs to the "Shirt" department
When product "12345" is imported
Then I should see the product "12345" in +Nellie version+
But I should +not+ see the product "12345" in +Mike version+

*Scenario 5: Filter out article depending on product which has +not+ been rolled out*
Given a product "12345" that has +not+ been rolled out 
And an article that relates to product "12345"
When article is imported
Then I should see the article in +Mike version+
But I should +not+ see the article in +Nellie version+

*Scenario 6: Filter out article depending on product which has been rolled out*
Given a product "12345" that has been rolled out 
And an article that relates to product "12345"
When article is imported
Then I should see the article in +Nellie version+
But I should +not+ see the article in +Mike version+

*Scenario 7: Filter out <imported entity> depending on order which has +not+ been rolled out*
Given an order "12345" that has +not+ been rolled out 
And a <imported entity> that relates to order "12345"
When <imported entity> is imported
Then I should see the <imported entity> in +Mike version+
But I should +not+ see the <imported entity> in +Nellie version+

*Scenario 8: Filter out <imported entity> depending on order which has been rolled out*
Given an order "12345" that has been rolled out 
And a <imported entity> that relates to order "12345"
When <imported entity> is imported
Then I should see the <imported entity> in +Nellie version+
But I should +not+ see the <imported entity> in +Mike version+

||Imported entity||
|BookingAdvice|
|DeliveryInformation|
|DespatchAdvice|
|GoodsRecievedEvent|
|ImportedExportedOrder (KL)|
|ManufacturingSpecification|
|OrderedProductSpecification|
|OrderReport|
|PriceTagOrderStatus|
|StartDeliveryInformation|
|VipOrder|

-A decision has been made to not import any data before season 7. We have a filter for this on the order import but it needs to be updated and the same filter needs to added to other imports that lookup the order.-

items.toString:
*Acc criteria for SIT test*
configuration "Accept all" is enough 
--------------------------------------------------------


During the gradual roll-out Mike and Nellie imports need to ignore data that does not belong to the current release. A filter will be introduced based on which department the data relates to. Initially all data is in Mike. Gradually data will be moved to Nellie (based on which department it belongs to).

*Scenario 1: Filter out orders +not+ rolled out*
Given a department "Shirts" that has +not+ been rolled out 
And an order "12345" that is for a product belonging to the "Shirt" department
When order "12345" is imported
Then I should see the order "12345" in +Mike version+
But I should +not+ see the order "12345" in +Nellie version+

*Scenario 2: Filter out orders rolled out*
Given a department "Shirts" that has been rolled out 
And an order "12345" that is for a product belonging to the "Shirt" department
When order "12345" is imported
Then I should see the order "12345" in +Nellie version+
But I should +not+ see the order "12345" in +Mike version+

*Scenario 3: Filter out products +not+ rolled out*
Given a department "Shirts" that has +not+ been rolled out 
And a product "12345" that belongs to the "Shirt" department
When product"12345" is imported
Then I should see the product "12345" in +Mike version+
But I should +not+ see the product "12345" in +Nellie version+

*Scenario 4: Filter out products rolled out*
Given a department "Shirts" that has been rolled out 
And a product "12345" that belongs to the "Shirt" department
When product "12345" is imported
Then I should see the product "12345" in +Nellie version+
But I should +not+ see the product "12345" in +Mike version+

*Scenario 5: Filter out article depending on product which has +not+ been rolled out*
Given a product "12345" that has +not+ been rolled out 
And an article that relates to product "12345"
When article is imported
Then I should see the article in +Mike version+
But I should +not+ see the article in +Nellie version+

*Scenario 6: Filter out article depending on product which has been rolled out*
Given a product "12345" that has been rolled out 
And an article that relates to product "12345"
When article is imported
Then I should see the article in +Nellie version+
But I should +not+ see the article in +Mike version+

*Scenario 7: Filter out <imported entity> depending on order which has +not+ been rolled out*
Given an order "12345" that has +not+ been rolled out 
And a <imported entity> that relates to order "12345"
When <imported entity> is imported
Then I should see the <imported entity> in +Mike version+
But I should +not+ see the <imported entity> in +Nellie version+

*Scenario 8: Filter out <imported entity> depending on order which has been rolled out*
Given an order "12345" that has been rolled out

Then I should see the <imported entity> in +Nellie version+
